<HEAD>
<TITLE> Operations Management major</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body><br><br><center><img src="/graphics/bjcrest.gif"></center><br>


<hr><center><h2>                  I. A BRIEF DESCRIPTION OF THE MAJOR</h2></center><BR>

The operations management major is designed to teach the Student the skills required to perform the
production function in both the manufacturing and service industries.  Among the many opportunities
awaiting the successful graduate are positions in process planning and scheduling, purchasing, expediting,
quality management, inventory control, and advanced study in graduate business schools, if desired.



<hr><center><h2>                         II. COURSE HIGHLIGHTS</h2></center><BR>

Here are some of the courses in the program you will especially enjoy--
<P>
     Principles of Management  In this introductory course you will develop an understanding
     of how a manager functions.  The many principles covered include planning, organizing,
     leadership, communication, and control procedures with a project simulating the
     management process using a computer-based simulation environment.
<P>
     Introductory Cost Accounting  This elective course provides an important foundation for
     operations management.  Here you will learn the nature and concepts of cost allocation,
     standard cost systems, budgeting procedures, performance measurement and human
     resource accounting.
<P>
     Production/Operations Management  This descriptive course covers a broad range of
     operations principles with a decision-based approach.  The entire operations management
     major centers on the topics presented here which include forecasting, scheduling, facility
     design, quality control, and much more!
<P>
     Quantitative Production Methods  An extension of the POM course outlined above, QPM
     applies the concepts learned to case problems using computer-based decision support tools
     to make the "number crunching" easier.  Most modern manufacturing facilities rely
     heavily on computers and this course gives valuable experience in that area.
     <hr><center><h2>                 III. A TYPICAL YEARLY COURSE SEQUENCE</h2></center><BR>

This is a suggested program of study for you.  You understand that other refinements to your program
can be made when you consult your faculty advisor at the time of your enrollment.
<P>
You will notice that some courses are listed as electives.  These electives give you the opportunity to
tailor your program to (1) secure the equivalent of a double major by adding additional courses to your
selected minor field of study, (2) add a third field of interest to your program of study which is almost
the same as having two minors, or (3) broaden your program by selecting individual courses you would
like to take to help you in your future ministry or for your own personal enjoyment.

<pre>
