<HEAD>
<TITLE> PASTORAL STUDIES major </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body><br><br><center><img src="/graphics/bjcrest.gif"></center><br>



<hr><center><h2>                       I. A BRIEF DESCRIPTION OF THE MAJOR</h2></center><BR>

The major in pastoral studies is primarily intended to prepare Students to serve in pastoral and associate
pastoral Ministries which support the preaching ministry of the senior pastor of a large church.


<hr><center><h2>                              II. COURSE HIGHLIGHTS</h2></center><BR>

Here are some of the courses in the program you will especially enjoy--<br>
<P>
       The Corinthian Epistles  In this class you will study Paul's instructions concerning church
       divisions, practical Christian living, Christian liberty, marriage and divorce, the gifts of
       the Spirit, and the place of Christian love; and his testimony and exhortations concerning
       the Christian ministry.
<P>
       Church and Home  This course will provide you with a study of the family life cycle
       (love, dating, courtship, engagement, marriage, postmarital adjustments, and children and
       youth in the home).  You will study with special attention the role of the church in
       meeting the needs of the family and those preparing for marriage.
<P>
       Biblical Themes  This is a course in which you will deal with the fundamental doctrines
       of Christianity as they are unfolded in Scripture, with attention given to the relationship
       of these doctrines to the central theme and messages of the Bible.  You will particularly
       study timely doctrinal questions such as ecclesiastical and personal separation; the
       inspiration, preservation, inerrancy, and authentiCity of the Word of God; and marriage
       and divorce.
<P>


<hr><center><h2>                      III. A TYPICAL YEARLY COURSE SEQUENCE</h2></center><BR>

This is a suggested program of study for you.  You understand that other refinements to your program
can be made when you consult your faculty advisor at the time of your enrollment.
<P>
You will notice that some courses are listed as electives.  These electives give you the opportunity to
tailor your program to (1) secure the equivalent of a double major by adding additional courses to your
selected minor field of study, (2) add a third field of interest to your program of study which is almost
the same as having two minors, or (3) broaden your program by selecting individual courses you would
like to take to help you in your future ministry or for your own personal enjoyment.
<P>
