<hr><center><h2>             IV. FACILITIES, EQUIPMENT, AND OPPORTUNITIES</h2></center><BR>

Physical therapy sessions are held weekly in our physio-therapy department located in the W.J. Barge
Memorial Hospital--a 79-bed facility located on the Campus.  By observing and assisting in the sessions,
you will be introduced to the practical aspects of your chosen field even before you begin your specialized
graduate study.
<P>
Dedicated exclusively for the use of science majors are two Mac Performas; a Mac IIci; a Power Mac
7100AV; two Mac LC's; one gel Electrophoresis apparatus.  Also available are Imagewriter II printers
and a LaserWriter IIg.  Some of the special equipment also used include a Pioneer Laser Disc player with
interface with Mac and hyperstack program.  The videodiscs used will also have access to a VHS
recorder with a video camera adapted for light microscopy.A Resources room in the Science Building supplements our extensive array of science-oriented books and
periodicals in the main library.  We also have a large collection of videocassettes, filmloops, and slides.
<P>
Two completely equipped computer laboratories are available for your use.  Among the available
equipment you will find:  486 DX33 and 486 DX2/66 machines, some configured for dual operating
system use (UNIX and DOS); laser printers; color scanners.  There is also a large selection of software
packages, including WordPerfect, Quattro Pro, Paradox, Borland C++, Pascal, and Borland Delphi.
<P>
The productions of the University Classic Players and Opera Association will enable you in four years
to see several Shakespearean plays and grand operas performed on Campus.  Every year there are also
frequent recitals and student performances in theater, speech, and music.
<P>
All Students have opportunity to participate in the University's athletic program.  Through a well-
integrated program of intramural athletic competition, a very high percentage of Student participation is
possible.  You will have the opportunity to compete in a wide variety of both team and individual sports
including soccer, speedball, basketball, softball, track, volleyball, tennis, swimming, badminton, judo,
table tennis, racquetball, archery, wrestling, and indoor soccer.
<P>
The annual spring <a href="/special/bibleconf/">Bible Conference</a> is one of the outstanding features of the University and Academy
year.  Your regular academic work will be suspended for the Conference, during which you will hear
messages from outstanding Bible teachers, pastors, and evangelists.
<P>
<a href="/aboutbju/places/library/">The modern Mack Library</A>, with 90,000 square feet of floor space and seating for over 1400 Students,
will give you access to 231,000 volumes, 1100 current periodical subscriptions, and more than 10,500
recordings.  An interlibrary loan program is available through OCLC, a national database, for books not
held in our library.
<P>
<a href="/whatsnew/chapel/">Chapel services are held every morning</A>, Monday through Friday.  These services are a source of great
inspiration to Students.  Four days a week the Chapel message is brought by the Chancellor or <a href="/aboutbju/president/">President</a>
when on the Campus, and in their absence by selected speakers.  One day each week the Chapel period
is devoted to the meetings of various literary societies.  Two meetings each month are devoted to
Missionary programs and speakers.
<P>
If you are planning to live on Campus, you will be glad to know that <a href="/studentlife/dorm/">all of our Dormitories are</A>air-
conditioned, have wall-to-wall carpeting, and have a phone in each room.  You will be able to make long-
