<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Pre-Veterinarian major </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body><br><br><center><img src="/graphics/bjcrest.gif"></center><br>

<hr><center><h2>                  I. A BRIEF DESCRIPTION OF THE MAJOR</h2></center><BR>

If becoming a veterinarian is important to you, we heartily recommend this major.  You will receive all
of the advantages of the traditional required courses which are designed to put you in the right "position"
to enter your professional veterinary medicine study, but you will experience in addition some unique
advantages.  Since BJU owns and operates its own beef and dairy farm, you will have contact with
animals throughout your undergraduate program.  Independent study and "honest-to-goodness" individual
attention will round out what you will be sure to describe as ". . . the best program I could imagine."


<hr><center><h2>                         II. COURSE HIGHLIGHTS</h2></center><BR>

Here are some of the courses in the program you will especially enjoy--<BR>
<P>
     Principles of Animal Science  This course will acquaint you with the livestock industry
     and animal agriculture.  You will study individual species, the types, their purposes, and
     their products.
<P>
     Comparative Vertebrate Anatomy  This is a laboratory course which will teach you the
     various classes of vertebrate animals with an emphasis upon comparing the anatomy of
     various systems.  You will have the opportunity to dissect representative specimens of
     several classes of animals.
<P>
     Biochemistry  For two semesters you will be immersed in the world of proteins,
     enzymes, carbohydrates, lipids, bioenergetics, glycolysis, citric acid cycle, electron
     transport, oxidative phosphorylation, amino acid metabolism, molecular physiology, and
     molecular transMission of genetic information.
<P>

<hr><center><h2>                 III. A TYPICAL YEARLY COURSE SEQUENCE</h2></center><BR>

This is a suggested program of study for you.  You understand that other refinements to your program
can be made when you consult your faculty advisor at the time of your enrollment.

You will notice that some courses are listed as electives.  These electives give you the opportunity to
tailor your program to broaden your overall program by selecting courses you would like to take for your
own personal enjoyment.
<P>
<PRE>
