</center><br><br></b>
<hr>
<a name="desc"><center><h2>I. A BRIEF DESCRIPTION OF THE MAJOR</h2></center></a>

<p>
<br>The accounting major provides preparation for (1) those who wish to
work as accountants with a business or corporation, (2) those who wish
to become Certified Public Accountants and work in public accounting, and
(3) those who wish to have Ministries as accountants or business managers
with churches or other Christian organizations.
<a name="course"><hr><center><h2>II. COURSE HIGHLIGHTS</h2></center></a>

<p>
Here are some of the courses in the program you will especially enjoy--
<p>
<br>Principles of Accounting This is a course you will use to begin developing
your basic accounting skills. You will learn the principles and procedures
which will prepare you for an active accounting career. Computer Applications
I As an accounting major, you will receive an introduction to the basic
capabilities of computers, types of computers and vocabulary. You will
be introduced to computer software including spread sheets, databases,
and graphics programs which will be useful in your chosen profession. Principles
of Management You will begin developing your understanding of the basic
management process by studying planning, organization, controlling, leadership,
and communication in the management field.

<p>
<a name="typical"><hr><center><h2>III. A TYPICAL YEARLY COURSE SEQUENCE</h2></center></a>

<p>
<br>This is a suggested program of study for you. You understand that other
refinements to your program can be made when you consult your faculty advisor
at the time of your enrollment. You will notice that some courses are listed
as electives. These electives give you the opportunity to tailor your program
to (1) secure the equivalent of a double major by adding additional courses
to your selected minor field of study, (2) add a third field of interest
to your program of study which is almost the same as having two minors,
or (3) broaden your program by selecting individual courses you would like
to take to help you in your future ministry or for your own personal enjoyment.
<br>

<pre>Freshman
 Orientation . . . . . . . . . . . 1  Orientation. . . . . . . . . . . . . .1
