<HEAD>
<TITLE> Public-interpersonal Communication major </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body><br><br><center><img src="/graphics/bjcrest.gif"></center><br>

<hr><center><h2>                  I. A BRIEF DESCRIPTION OF THE MAJOR</h2></center><BR>

The public-interpersonal communication major emphasizes skill development in public speaking and
interpersonal communication as well as an understanding of the communication process.  It is a package
of theory and performance designed to meet the needs of today's communication-driven world.



<hr><center><h2>                         II. COURSE HIGHLIGHTS</h2></center><BR>

Here are some of the courses in the program you will especially enjoy--<BR>
<P>
     Interpersonal Communication  This course will give insights on interviewing, conflict
     resolution, and nonverbal behavior.
<P>
     Organizational Communication  Here you will discover why good communication is vital
     to an organization and how to help an organization diagnose and improve communication
     with its members and the public.
<P>
     Persuasion  Here you will learn the different theories of persuasion and apply them in
     a persuasive campaign.
<P>
     Communication Internship  You will have hands-on experience working with a local
     business or local media in some aspect of communication.
<P>


<hr><center><h2>                 III. A TYPICAL YEARLY COURSE SEQUENCE</h2></center><BR>

This is a suggested program of study for you.  You understand that other refinements to your program
can be made when you consult your faculty advisor at the time of your enrollment.
<P>
You will notice that some courses are listed as electives.  These electives give you the opportunity to
tailor your program to (1) secure the equivalent of a double major by adding additional courses to your
selected minor field of study, (2) add a third field of interest to your program of study which is almost
the same as having two minors, or (3) broaden your program by selecting individual courses you would
like to take to help you in your future ministry or for your own personal enjoyment.
<P>
<PRE>
Freshman
 Orientation                    1
 English                        3
 Science, Mathematics, or
   <a href="/academic/colleges/cas/math/cps/">Computer Science</a>*            3
 History of Civilization        3
