<HEAD>
<TITLE> Social Studies Education major </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body><br><br><center><img src="/graphics/bjcrest.gif"></center><br>

<hr><center><h2>                                      I. A BRIEF DESCRIPTION OF THE MAJOR</h2></center><BR>

We are preparing our Students to be good social studies teachers by also being good leaders, citizens, and
communicators in their homes and communities.


<hr><center><h2>                                             II. COURSE HIGHLIGHTS</h2></center><BR>

Here are some of the courses in the program you will especially enjoy--<br>
<P>
            General Teaching Methods  This course has been evaluated by our graduates as one of
            the most practical they have taken at BJU.  It will give you the opportunity to prepare
            lesson plans, teach lessons, and be videotaped and evaluated by an experienced instructor.
            You will also get "hands on" experience in the University's well-equipped media center,
            where you will learn how to operate and use state-of-the-art audiovisual equipment.

<P>
            History of Civilization  You will especially enjoy this class, which is taught by
            Dr. Edward Panosian.  This lecture class is supplemented by smaller, personal classes
            where you will have many opportunities to ask questions and gain insights you may have
            missed in the lectures.  In this class you will learn the complete History of civilization as
            "His Story," that is, the story of God's providential workings through nations and men.
<P>

            Directed Teaching  Here you will have a chance to "try your wings" by teaching under
            the supervision of an experienced teacher.  You will begin gradually and work into
            handling a teacher's normal load.


<hr><center><h2>                                     III. A TYPICAL YEARLY COURSE SEQUENCE</h2></center><BR>

This is a suggested program of study for you.  You understand that other refinements to your program
can be made when you consult your faculty advisor at the time of your enrollment.
<P>
You will notice that some courses are listed as electives.  These electives give you the opportunity to
tailor your program to (1) secure the equivalent of a double major by adding additional courses to your
selected minor field of study, (2) add a third field of interest to your program of study which is almost
the same as having two minors, or (3) broaden your program by selecting individual courses you would
like to take to help you in your future ministry or for your own personal enjoyment.
<pre>
